  "prompt": "Why do some emails end in \".edu\"?",
  "response": "Emails that end in \".edu\" are associated with educational institutions, primarily colleges and universities in the United States. The \".edu\" top-level domain (TLD) is restricted for use by accredited postsecondary institutions, which helps to establish a credible online presence for these organizations. \n\nThe purpose of this restriction is to prevent misuse and ensure that only legitimate educational entities can use the \".edu\" designation. This domain is commonly used for official communications from educational institutions, and email addresses ending with \".edu\" are typically assigned to faculty, staff, and students of those institutions. Additionally, having an \".edu\" email address can sometimes grant access to educational discounts, resources, and software specifically aimed at students and educators.",
